SIMPLE: intervention
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intervention
<hw>In`ter*ven"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>interventio</ets> an interposition: cf. F.
<ets>intervention</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of intervening; interposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sound is shut out by the <qex>intervention</qex> of that lax
membrane.</q> <rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any interference that may affect the interests of
others; especially, of one or more states with the affairs of another;
-- the intervention of one state in the affairs of another is typically
unwelcome by the state being intervened in, but some cases of mediation
between states may be called <ex>intervention</ex>. Opposed to
<contr>nonintervention</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us decide our quarrels at home, without the
<qex>intervention</qex>, of any foreign power.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Civil Law)</fld> <def>The act by which a third
person, to protect his own interest, interposes and becomes a party to a
suit pending between other parties.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interventor</ent>⟦br⟧
